A vintage 1950s-style illustration of a frustrated person sitting at a retro wooden desk, tangled in an absurdly long telephone cord that spirals chaotically around the room, connecting to an old rotary phone. The person holds a crumpled letter in one hand while the other hand gestures in exasperation toward the ceiling. On the desk, a thick stack of unopened envelopes and a primitive computer monitor displaying static. The color palette features muted teals, burnt oranges, and cream tones typical of mid-century advertising art. The scene conveys bureaucratic absurdity and communication breakdown, with the telephone cord forming maze-like loops that visually represent the endless runaround of customer service.
